Spock. It’s interesting to consider how the integration will work and what specific testing features I can implement. I want to make sure everything fits together smoothly in this setup!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Investigating runtime classes**\\n\\nI’m considering if runtime classes should be used instead of AST. I might look into using the \\\"Sputnik\\\" runner. Perhaps I need to inspect the JAR file? I should think about whether I need to fetch the local Gradle cache for this as well. Using the find command could be helpful in tracking down what I need. There's definitely a process here that I'm trying to streamline!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_43uXdNn774HWCTUeTv8MXnzt|fc_03e86946db7ddd75016a27079c94908194b2e14bbda3eded9b", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1/org.spockframework/spock-core/1.0-groovy-2.4 -type f | sed 's#^#/#' | head -20", "timeout": 10}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "oca/gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 717, "output": 624, "cacheRead": 25088, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 26429, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1780942729275, "responseId": "resp_03e86946db7ddd75016a270789ce8881948633348d4c9d1766"}}
